150,tutor to whom essay is assigned,student.care@gradready.com.au,An essay is available to mark,essay marking,essay submission by student,<!DOCTYPE html>
Consider the following comments and develop a piece of writing in response to one or more of them. Your writing will be judged on the quality of your response to the theme
column2: how well you organise and present your point of view, and how effectively you express yourself. You will not be judged on the views or attitudes you express.

column1: The causes of events are ever more interesting than the events themselves.
History is but a confused heap of facts.
Anybody can make history. Only a great man can write it.
The history of the world is but the biography of great men.
God cannot alter the past, but historians can.

Grandparents are commonly associated with the wise in the eyes of their grandchildren. Parents may preferentially let their parents look after their children instead of childminders. This happens not only because there are no attached charges but also because the little ones can grasp precious life lessons from their grandparents. This reminds me of my childhood days when I was thrilled to listen to my granny’s episodes of her adolescence. I still remember her enthusiasm when she was talking about her first car, a 500 FIAT, and her first meeting with my grandad. Surprisingly, negative episodes were not missing in her story telling. Her feelings of anger, sadness and fear after discovering the exportation of her dad, my great grandad, to the German concentration camps has remained vivid in my mind.  What’s more, I became so intrigued by the background events of World War II that I started reading books about it. Nevertheless, this early passion of mine vanished in secondary school. Learning about the past events in school turned out to be my least favourite activity. Yet, I have recently realised that history is so much more than a list of unrelated facts and dates.

The utility of history has been undermined by the education authorities so that in many European countries history is no longer a mandatory subject. Particularly, public schools have adopted history as optional or even excluded it from the curriculum. Both directions are likely to come to the same conclusion. In fact, when students are given the option to study history, they often do not include it in their list of choices and rather pick apparently more interesting subjects. This is the case of most Irish secondary school pupils. The very few young lovers of history cannot help but become acquainted of the past through reading history novels and/or taking history as an extracurricular commitment. As a result, history teaching and history learning seems to be unusual these days since fewer and fewer students are taking it as an academic subject. Along this line, history is likely to become part of the past, rather than the present, thereby only remaining in the education of our parents and grandparents.

Notwithstanding, do we really want our future generations to be ignorant of the story of our loved ones? Perhaps, labelling history as boring and useless may be due to the current simplistic approach of history teaching and learning. In simpler words, how can any individual love learning off random events by heart for their upcoming exams and be expected to like it. We would rather solve maths problems or reading a poem, right? This may be because most history educators are behaving like living history books. Some of them are even scared of ‘teaching’ history due to their effect on increasing yawning during class. As a result, when asking about a salient summary of the Great War or WWII, the vast majority of us would limit their answer to a ‘I don’t know, who cares, etc’. But hopefully when asked for the full date of national independence of French Revolution they rarely miss the right answer. History is not just about remembering facts and dates. It is a more complex, interesting and intriguing matter than that. Learning the true history signifies getting to know the rationale behind past events. Literally, it means putting ourselves in the shoes of past characters, their enemies, or friends, thereby understanding their mentality followed by formulating our opinions on their actions. This approach to history learning looks more appealing, doesn’t it?  To tackle the alarming threat of the extinction of history in school, education providers must urgently implement more enjoyable methods of teaching history in class, for example by engaging the students in a play representing a historical episode, and for the older pupils by triggering a discussion on the consequences of an important past event and/or by analysing landmark manuscripts. As I anticipated above, history of events should be read as a logical progression of events that shapes individual actions and emotions. In fact, history is not only about big events and leaders. It is mainly about what ordinary people felt, accomplished and how they behaved in the public and private setting. My granny’s past is therefore an essential part of it. By looking at history as a rational, rather than chronological, series of events, by discovering the rationale behind them and the customs of our family ancestors we will surely appreciate history a bit more. Furthermore, we will consider our past as a great source of reflection for our future actions. In fact, we are indeed the product of the past. Our realisation that we can learn from past episodes may actually be the only hope for us, as a united community, to make history revive again in the new generations to come.

155,essay's student,student.care@gradready.com.au,A tutor responded to your essay,essay marking,when tutor respond to essay,<!DOCTYPE html>
Melis Gezer  , responded to your essay
Thank you for submitting this practice GAMSAT essay. Well done on responding to the theme of 'history'. I hope you find the following feedback helpful.

Your introduction was really awesome! It was super engaging and also very interesting. I kept reading with curiosity to see how you were going to unpack the theme and was worried it would not be explicit enough or well related to the overarching theme, but you did a good job in the latter half of your introduction really tying it all together. You also wrote this paragraph really well in terms of your language, expression and grammar. Keep up the great work with such eloquent and engaging introductions - it really sets a nice tone and standard for the essay to come.

Well done also on your first body paragraph. It had a nice topic sentence and an example embedded into it. Although I was not entirely sure of where the example of Ireland started and stopped and the specificity of it was not as clear. Is there a trend in that country? What does it demonstrate? Remember to not only embed an example but really explicitly discuss the example and relate it back to your overall purpose. Everything we place into these time and length limited essays should be purposeful. Analyse all examples! They should be used to demonstrate a point, not just thrown in there. Well done on a nice linkage sentence to finish this paragraph off. This tied it all back to the theme which was good.

After your first body paragraph, the structure of your essay became less clear. However your writing was still good. You still had a really strong author's voice. I wonder perhaps if your conclusion did not get separated from the second body paragraph? I was unsure. Remember to always try and include a conclusion, even if it is just a short and concise couple of sentences. This just really serves to conclude your remarks, summarises the key points and reiterates the purpose. It is a really important feature for a strong essay. Nonetheless, well done on expressing your views with passion and creativity - they really came across through your words. It was once again engaging, involving the reader and inviting them to think about what you were arguing. This is a great skill - keep up this application! One note of caution would be to make sure you state truths with assertion and opinions less definitively, for example, you state ""This may be because most history educators are behaving like living history books. Some of them are even scared of ‘teaching’ history due to their effect on increasing yawning during class."". Do we know that teachers are 'scared'? I would argue this is not a fact for all teachers. You should state such things less definitively - i.e., some teachers may be scared.
Like I have mentioned, this was a well written essay with very minor errors in terms of language and grammar. Two errors that I would like to point out for future reference include:
<li>""We would rather solve maths problems or reading a poem, right?"" --&gt
column2: remember to be consistent with tense, solve maths problems should be coupled with read a poem - not 'reading'

column1: <li>""the vast majority of us would limit their answer to"" --&gt
column2: if you state 'us' then this should be accompanied with 'our' not 'their'

column1: Well done again on this essay. Keep up the great work, I have seen great improvement with your essay submissions! Well done Federica.

Particularly, public schools have adopted history as optional or even excluded it from the curriculum. Both directions are likely to come to the same conclusion. In fact, when students are given the option to study history, they often do not include it in their list of choices and rather pick apparently more interesting subjects. This is the case of most Irish secondary school pupils. The very few young lovers of history cannot help but become acquainted of the past through reading history novels and/or taking history as an extracurricular commitment. As a result, history teaching and history learning seems to be unusual these days since fewer and fewer students are taking it as an academic subject. Along this line, history is likely to become part of the past, rather than the present, thereby only remaining in the education of our parents and grandparents.

Notwithstanding, do we really want our future generations to be ignorant of the story of our loved ones? Perhaps, labelling history as boring and useless may be due to the current simplistic approach of history teaching and learning. In simpler words, how can any individual love learning off random events by heart for their upcoming exams and be expected to like it. We would rather solve maths problems or reading a poem, right? This may be because most history educators are behaving like living history books. Some of them are even scared of ‘teaching’ history due to their effect on increasing yawning during class. As a result, when asking about a salient summary of the Great War or WWII, the vast majority of us would limit their answer to a ‘I don’t know, who cares, etc’. But hopefully when asked for the full date of national independence of French Revolution they rarely miss the right answer. History is not just about remembering facts and dates. It is a more complex, interesting and intriguing matter than that. Learning the true history signifies getting to know the rationale behind past events. Literally, it means putting ourselves in the shoes of past characters, their enemies, or friends, thereby understanding their mentality followed by formulating our opinions on their actions. This approach to history learning looks more appealing, doesn’t it?  To tackle the alarming threat of the extinction of history in school, education providers must urgently implement more enjoyable methods of teaching history in class, for example by engaging the students in a play representing a historical episode, and for the older pupils by triggering a discussion on the consequences of an important past event and/or by analysing landmark manuscripts. As I anticipated above, history of events should be read as a logical progression of events that shapes individual actions and emotions. In fact, history is not only about big events and leaders. It is mainly about what ordinary people felt, accomplished and how they behaved in the public and private setting. My granny’s past is therefore an essential part of it. By looking at history as a rational, rather than chronological, series of events, by discovering the rationale behind them and the customs of our family ancestors we will surely appreciate history a bit more. Furthermore, we will consider our past as a great source of reflection for our future actions. In fact, we are indeed the product of the past. Our realisation that we can learn from past episodes may actually be the only hope for us, as a united community, to make history revive again in the new generations to come.

column1: You have likely heard about the rise in community transmission and cases of COVID-19 across the country.

Unfortunately with the course dates commencing so soon, we felt it was vital for us to make a proactive decision in determining the format of our Live Courses. This is to ensure that we have time to make necessary adjustments so that the quality of education delivered to you, is up to par with our standards, and your expectations.
After taking various factors into consideration, including our perspective that things may get worse, before they get better, as well as our broader responsibility to the community, we'
column2: ve decided that it would be unwise to run our upcoming course in a face-to-face format in Melbourne, Sydney, Brisbane and Adelaide. We will be transitioning to an interactive webinar format via Zoom for both our January and February courses, including revision weekends and mock exams.

column1: So to re-emphasize, we will NOT be running ANY in person courses leading up to the March 2022 GAMSAT in ALL locations, except for Perth. The situation in Perth is being monitored closely and is subject to change.

Further details regarding your course timetable, Zoom links and other relevant information will be released early next week, so please ensure that you have our @gradready.com.au email addresses white-listed (instructions for this for most popular email services can be found here).
Despite the change in format, you can rest assured that our top priority will always be providing our students with the best experience possible.
We sincerely apologise for any inconveniences and disappointments caused by this decision.
As we understand that students often have a preference between online and in-person classes,
we are able to offer the following options to those enrolled in the January or February Course:
1) Remain Enrolled in the January/February Course
If you would like to take this option please submit a support ticket on our website via GetClarity under the tag 2. Course Administration advising us of your intent.

You may also downgrade to your respective Online (Comprehensive) or (Essentials) course and waive the normal administrative fee. For Complete Care students, if you decide to avail this option you will receive a refund equal to Attendance (Comprehensive) students, and will be able to retain your unused private tutoring sessions. I am very well thanks for asking.
I do appreciate you writing to follow-up on my feedback regarding the Introduction.

It is absolutely right of you to be concerned about the amount of time you spend on each phase of writing (planning, writing, editing and proofreading). When time and space permits it would help you stand out from the many other essays to include as much detail as you can in your Intros. What I mean by ""acknowledging the examples"" that serve your key arguments is to simply mention them.

You might say, ""Media outlets have the power to dictate the ""news"" of the day, to meet public interest as well as ensuring sales. Two important social issues of our time: the debate over gun control in the US, in the wake of mass shootings such as those occurring recently in Miami
column2: and the refugee crises that affect many countries including Australia, involving refugee camps such as Nauru, are systematically and simultaneously exploited (as front-page news items) and then neglected (missing altogether from the headlines). As these issues persist over a long period of time, news media outlets could do more to treat such stories with careful and consistent consideration.

column1: It would only take a few moments to incorporate mention of the example -- just drop it in at the end of the sentence.

The wonderful thing about feedback is that you have the chance to reflect upon your own writing and make informed decisions about how you can develop your own approach. If you feel confident and comfortable simply mentioning your key ideas and arguments, then run with that. Sometimes under the pressure of timed exam conditions, there are trade-offs to be made. My feedback in relation to the Intro was just an observation/suggestion, so don't feel compelled to adopt that approach.
Hopefully this helps clarify things? Feel free to write again should you need some further context!
